The original callback passed two success values — `(null, valid, invalidCount)`. Since `async` functions can only return a single value, the pair is bundled into `{ validRecords, invalidCount }` and destructured at the call site. The result object shape in `processDataPipeline` is unchanged.

### `fs.promises` import
`require('fs').promises` gives the built-in promisified versions of `readFile`/`writeFile` with identical signatures (minus the callback), so encoding flags like `'utf-8'` are passed through unmodified.

